{"cursor":"15636","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'alwar' or 'azhwars' (, ÄzvÄrkaá¸· , âthose immersed in godâ) were Tamil poet-\nsaints of south India who lived between the 6th and 9th centuries AD and\nespoused âemotional devotionâ or bhakti to Visnu-Krishna in their songs of\nlonging, ecstasy and service. Sri Vaishnava orthodoxy posits the\nnumber of alvars as ten, though there are other references that include Andal\nand Madhurakavi, making the number twelve. The devotional outpourings\nof Alvars, composed during the early medieval period of Tamil history, helped\nrevive the bhakti movement, through their hymns of worship to Vishnu and his\nAvatars. They praised 108 of this deity's holy abodes in their hymns, known as\nthe Divya Desams. Vaishanava bhakti literature was an all-India phenomenon which\nstarted in the 6th or 7th century AD in the Tamil-speaking region of South\nIndia, with twelve Alvar (one immersed in God) saint-poets, who wrote devotional\nsongs. The religion of Alvar poets, which included a woman poet, Andal, was\ndevotion to God through love (bhakti), and in the ecstasy of such devotions they\nsang hundreds of songs which embodied both depth of feeling and felicity of\nexpressions. Together with the contemporary sixty three Saiva\nNayanars, they are accounted as South India's 75 Apostles of Bhakti because of\ntheir importance in the rise of the Hindu Bhakti movement. The collection of\ntheir hymns is known as [[Divya Prabandha]].\n\nThe Bhakti literature that sprang from Alvars has contributed to the\nestablishment and sustenance of a culture that broke away from the ritual-\noriented Vedic religion and rooted itself in devotion as the only path for\nsalvation. In addition they helped to make the Tamil religious life\nindependent of a knowledge of Sanskrit. {{cite web|\ntitle=About Alvars\n| publisher=divyadesamonline.com|\nurl=http://www.divyadesamonline.com/alwars.asp| accessdate= 2007-07-02\n|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070621230057/http://www.divyadesamon-\nline.com/alwars.asp  |archivedate = 2007-06-\n21}} As part of the legacy of the Alvars, five Vaishnava philosophical\ntraditions (sampradayas) have developed at the later stages. {{cite book\n | last1= Mittal| first1=S. G. R.|last2= Thursby year = 2006 title = Religions\n | of South Asia: An Introduction publisher = Routledge isbn =9780203970027\n|page=27 }}\n","linknr":302,"url":"Alvars","recorded":1374545192,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Alvars&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Alvars&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Alwar","/wiki/Alvars,_Iran","/wiki/File:RH_Hindu_Temple_5.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/RH_Hindu_Temple_5.jpg/200px-RH_Hindu_Temple_5.jpg","/wiki/File:RH_Hindu_Temple_5.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Tamil_language","/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Tamil","/wiki/Tamil_people","/wiki/Bhakti","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Andal","#cite_note-2","/wiki/History_of_Tamil_Nadu","/wiki/Bhakti","/wiki/Vishnu","/wiki/Avatar","/wiki/Divya_Desam","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Saiva","/wiki/Nayanars","/wiki/South_India%27s_75_Apostles_of_Bhakti","/wiki/Bhakti_moveme